MB2LME > MISR Level 1B2 Local Mode Ellipsoid Radiance Data 2013-11-05T15:14:10.990Z revision 2003-03-24T10:09:48.553Z creation 2 MB2LME MISR Level 1B2 Local Mode Ellipsoid Radiance Data MB2LME2 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Veljko Milord Jovanovic Technical Contact for Science 818-354-1705 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA Veljko.Jovanovic@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B2 Local Mode ellipsoid-projected Radiance parameters;See ProductionDateTime for Published date.
This file contains the ellipsoid projected TOA parameters for the single local mode scene,resampled to WGS84 ellipsoid Version Description: Added SP_AM_MISR_ProductVersion PSA

The MISR Instrument can also acquire data in what is referred to as Local Mode,which provides high resolution(unaveraged) images in all 4 bands of all 9 cameras for selected Earth targets.Data obtained from Local Mode sites will be used for new algorithm development,specialized research,calibration,field validation,instrument intercomparisons,or other purposes at the MISR SCF.This parameter provides Local Mode data which has not been corrected for topography,but has been projected to SOM.

MI1B1 > MISR Level 1B1 Radiance Data 2013-11-05T15:14:14.923Z revision 2003-03-24T10:17:41.526Z creation 2 MI1B1 MISR Level 1B1 Radiance Data Carol J. Bruegge Technical Contact for Science 818-354-4956 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA Carol.Bruegge@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first. principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B1 Radiance Data;See ProductionDateTime for Published Date.
This is the Level 1B1 Product containing the DNs radiometrically-scaled to radiances with no geometric resampling Version Description: Added SP_AM_MISR_ProductVersion PSA

Level 1B1 processing is required as a precursor to all higher level products.Here,the radiometric calibration coefficients are used to convert raw DN counts to a radiance scale.Additionally,image sharpening is performed,to provide accurate radiometry even when viewing contrasting scenes.These data are not archived,but of interest to investigators who require the highest accuracy in their data.At the next processing step,Level 1B2,the data are resampled,registered,and geolocated.

MI1B2E > MISR Level 1B2 Ellipsoid Data 2013-11-05T15:14:15.436Z revision 2005-03-23T10:54:12.613Z creation 3 MI1B2E MISR Level 1B2 Ellipsoid Data MI1B2E3 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Veljko Milord Jovanovic Technical Contact for Science 818-354-1705 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA Veljko.Jovanovic@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B2 ellipsoid-projected Radiance parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published date.

This file contains Ellipsoid-projected TOA Radiance,resampled at the surface and topographically corrected, as well as geometrically corrected by PGE22 Version Description: Incremented VersionID value to 3 to indicate the new geometrically corrected L1B2 Ellipsoid product

MISR Level 2 TOA/Cloud retrievals require the radiances from all 9 cameras of MISR to be projected to a surface defined by the reference WGS84 ellipsoid.It is on this surface camera-to-camera stereo matching will be performed to determine cloud altitude. Topographic distortions are removed.Corrections due to errors in the supplied Navigation and attitude data are obtained during Terrain-projected parameter processing and are applied to these parameters.

MI1B2T > MISR Level 1B2 Terrain Data 2013-11-05T15:14:16.696Z revision 2005-03-23T10:54:37.660Z creation 3 MI1B2T MISR Level 1B2 Terrain Data MI1B2T3 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Veljko Milord Jovanovic Technical Contact for Science 818-354-1705 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA Veljko.Jovanovic@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B2 terrain-projected Radiance parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published date.

This file contains Terrain-projected TOA Radiance,resampled at the surface and topographically corrected, as well as geometrically corrected by PGE22 Version Description: Incremented VersionID value to 3 to indicate the new geometrically corrected L1B2 Terrain product

Both the MISR Level 2 Aerosol/surface retrievals and the cloud mask generation with the MISR Level 2 TOA/cloud retrievals need radiances from all 9 cameras of MISR to be coregistered and projected to the earth's surface using a common map projection,which ensures that the same boundary conditions apply to each of the 9 views.This involves corrections for topographic distortion,band displacement,and errors in the supplied navigation and attitude data.

The MISR Instrument can also acquire data in what is referred to as Local Mode,which provides high resolution(unaveraged) images in all 4 bands of all 9 cameras for selected earthtargets.Data obtained from Local Mode sites will be used for new algorithm development,Specialized research,calibration,field validation,instrument intercomparisons,or other purposes at the MISR SCF.This parameter provides swath Local Mode data which has not been geometrically resampled.

MIB2GEOP > MISR Geometric Parameters 2013-11-05T15:14:48.200Z revision 2003-03-24T10:23:12.660Z creation 2 MIB2GEOP MISR Geometric Parameters MIB2GEOP2 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Veljko Milord Jovanovic Technical Contact for Science 818-354-1705 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA Veljko.Jovanovic@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B2 Geometric Parameters;See ProductionDateTime for Published date.
This file contains the Geometric Parameters which measure the sun and view angles at the reference ellipsoid Version Description: Added SP_AM_MISR_ProductVersion PSA

Needed by all MISR Level 2 science algorithms for several types of retrievals are the MISR L1B2 Geometric Parameters which supply the sun and view angles on the reference WGS84 ellipsoid relative to a normal to that surface,as well as azimuth angles relative to Local North.The sun zenith and azimuth angles are determined from Earth and Sun ephemerides at the time of viewing.The view zenith and azimuth angles are based upon the reported spacecraft attitude and position.

Martonchik Technical Contact for Science 818-354-2207 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA John.Martonchik@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 2 Aerosol parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published Date.
This is the Level 2 Aerosol Product.It contains Aerosol optical depth and particle type, with associated atmospheric data. Version Description: Added SP_AM_MISR_ProductVersion PSA

To study the magnitude and natural variability in space & time of sunlight & cloud interactions with aerosols in the earth's atmosphere & to determine their effect on climate;to improve knowledge of sources,sinks & global budgets of aerosols; & to provide atmospheric correction inputs for surface imaging data acquired by MISR & other instruments that are simultaniously viewing the same portion of the earth,for the purpose of making better quantitative estimates of surface reflectance.

Martonchik Technical Contact for Science 818-354-2207 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA John.Martonchik@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK Land Surface Parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published Date.

This Level 2 FIRSTLOOK Land Surface product contains directional reflectance properties,albedo(spectral & PAR integrated),FPAR,radiation parameters & terrain-referenced geometric parameters, produced using ancillary input from the previous time period. Version Description: Initial Version

To characterize bidirectional reflectance properties of terrestrial surface,as a function of space,time and surface type;to study, on a global basis,the magnitude and natural variability in space and time of sunlight absorption and scattering by the earth's surface;to provide improved measures of land surface classification and dynamics in conjunction with MODIS.

MIL2TCAF > MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Albedo parameters 2013-11-05T15:14:54.936Z revision 2007-05-16T15:08:12.993Z creation 1 MIL2TCAF MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Albedo parameters MIL2TCAF1 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Roger Unknown Davies Technical Contact for Science 520-621-6844 Institute of Atmospheric Physics, University of Arizona, PAS Building #81 Tucson AZ 85721 USA davies@air.atmo.arizona.edu 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Albedo parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published Date.

This is the Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Albedo Product. It contains local,restrictive, and expansive albedo, with associated data, produced using ancillary inputs from the previous time period. Version Description: Initial Version
To study, on a global basis, the effects of different types of cloud fields on the spectral solar radiance and irradiance reflected to space, including spatial and temporal dependences.

MIL2TCSF > MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Stereo parameters 2013-11-05T15:14:57.603Z revision 2007-05-16T15:09:09.120Z creation 1 MIL2TCSF MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Stereo parameters MIL2TCSF1 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Roger Unknown Davies Technical Contact for Science 520-621-6844 Institute of Atmospheric Physics, University of Arizona, PAS Building #81 Tucson AZ 85721 USA davies@air.atmo.arizona.edu 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR science team;processed/stored at Langley DAAC;product is the MISR Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Stereo parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published Date.

This is the Level 2 FIRSTLOOK TOA/Cloud Stereo Product. It contains the Stereoscopically Derived winds, heights and cloud mask along with associated data, produced using ancillary inputs (TASC) from the previous time period. Version Description: Initial Version
To study, on a global basis, the effects of different types of cloud fields on the spectral solar radiance and irradiance reflected to space, including spatial and temporal dependences.

MIL2TCSP > MISR Level 2 TOA/Cloud Height and Motion parameters 2014-01-31T10:09:18.248Z revision 2012-01-30T15:05:05.263Z creation 1 MIL2TCSP MISR Level 2 TOA/Cloud Height and Motion parameters MIL2TCSP1 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId Roger Unknown Davies Technical Contact for Science 64 9 923 8868 Department of Physics, University of Auckland, Building 303, 38 Princes Street Auckland Not Applicable 1142 NZL r.davies@auckland.ac.nz 9-5 New Zealand time weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 2 TOA/Cloud Height and Motion parameters;See ProductionDateTime for published Date.

This is the Level 2 TOA/Cloud Product containing the Stereo Heights, Stereoscopically Derived Cloud Mask (SDCM) and Cloud Motion Vectors with associated data. Version Description: Initial version of product.
To study, on a global basis, the distribution and correlation of cloud heights and motion vectors as well as case studies of particular scenes.

MIRCCM > MISR radiometric camera-by-camera Cloud Mask 2013-11-05T15:15:35.983Z revision 2004-06-14T08:32:50.420Z creation 4 MIRCCM MISR radiometric camera-by-camera Cloud Mask Dave J. Diner Technical Contact for Science 818-354-6319 4800 Oak Grove Drive Pasadena CA 91109 USA David.Diner@jpl.nasa.gov 9-5 Pacific weekdays Contact by email first principalInvestigator The data used in this study were produced by the MISR Science Team;processed/stored at the Langley DAAC;Product is the MISR Level 1B2 Radiometric camera-by-camera parameters;See ProductionDateTime for Published date.

This file contains the Radiometric camera-by-camera Cloud Mask dataset. It is used to determine whether a scene is classified as clear or cloudy. A new parameter has been added to indicate dust over ocean. This version of the ESDT is used by MISR PGE 13. Version Description: Updated ESDT version/contents for stand-alone usage with new PGE 13 (RCCM)

The RCCM is used during geophysical parameter retrievals. In the TOA/Cloud Product,RCCM is combined with stereoscopically derived cloud mask to 1) establish values of the Reflecting Level Reference Altitude,2) determine how a scene is classified for choosing angular integration coefficients for establishing TOA albedos,and 3) calculate regional scene classifiers. Retrieval of Aerosol/Surface Product properties requires the abscence of clouds,for retrieval assumptions to be valid.

This file contains the FIRSTLOOK Radiometric camera-by-camera Cloud Mask (RCCM) dataset produced using ancillary inputs (RCCT) from the previous time period. It is used to determine whether a scene is clear, cloudy or dusty (over ocean). Version Description: Initial Version

The RCCM is used during geophysical parameter retrievals. In the TOA/Cloud Product,RCCM is combined with stereoscopically derived cloud mask to 1) establish values of the Reflecting Level Reference Altitude,2) determine how a scene is classified for choosing angular integration coefficients for establishing TOA albedos,and 3) calculate regional scene classifiers. Retrieval of Aerosol/Surface Product properties requires the abscence of clouds,for retrieval assumptions to be valid.

TL1BL > TES/Aura L1B Spectra Limb 2013-11-05T15:16:30.246Z revision 2010-08-11T09:14:25.436Z creation 4 TL1BL TES/Aura L1B Spectra Limb TL1BL4 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId The data used in this study were produced by the TES Science Team at the TES SIPS and archived at the Langley DAAC. See ProductionDateTime for Published date.

The L1B Limb granule consists of radiometrically calibrated spectra & associated NESR, observed at 0.025 cm-1 resolution for an entire Global Survey & organized by observed target scene & instrument parameters such as focal plane/filter & pixel ID. Version Description: BT11 microwindows updated to remove a small atmospheric contamination. The apparent laser frequency is now determined for every run to account for small long term drift.

The L1B Limb Calibrated Spectra file consists of radiometrically calibrated spectra and associated NESR observed at 0.025 cm-1 resolution. These spectra are the input measurements to the Level 2 retrieval algorithm that will produce the TES Standard Data Products. The spectra can be used directly as radiance measurements of the earth and atmosphere.

TL2ANC > TES/Aura L2 Ancillary Product 2013-11-05T15:16:36.523Z revision 2013-03-29T11:55:36.193Z creation 6 TL2ANC TES/Aura L2 Ancillary Product TL2ANC6 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId The data used in this study were produced by the TES Science Team at the TES SIPS and archived at the Langley DAAC. See ProductionDateTime for Published date.

Atmospheric vertical profile estimates and associated errors (diagonals and covariance matrices), along with retrieved surface temperature, cloud effective optical depth, column estimates, quality flags, averaging kernels and a priori constraint vectors. Version Description: New O3 climatology data. Updated Methane climatology data. Updated max Optical Path Difference values. New Chi2 quality flag reported. New desert emissivity flag. Updated GMAO a priori values.

The L2 Ancillary Product file consists of measured and static parameters common to all species, such as Surface Pressure and Emissivity. The file is used in conjunction with other L2 species files for detailed studies. There are separate data (Swath) objects corresponding to the Nadir and three Limb views. Each row (nTimes dimension) lines up with the data objects in the species files.

TL2SUP > TES/Aura L2 Supplemental Profiles 2013-11-05T15:17:22.883Z revision 2013-03-29T11:55:49.666Z creation 6 TL2SUP TES/Aura L2 Supplemental Profiles TL2SUP6 gov.nasa.gcmd DIFEntryId The data used in this study were produced by the TES Science Team at the TES SIPS and archived at the Langley DAAC. See ProductionDateTime for Published date.

Input data to the TES radiance forward model. These are profiles generated from climatology databases to be used in the forward model calculation but are not retrieved parameters. Version Description: New O3 climatology data. Updated Methane climatology data. Updated max Optical Path Difference values. New Chi2 quality flag reported. New desert emissivity flag. Updated GMAO a priori values.

These profiles should only be used in the context of understanding the inputs to the TES forward model and retrieval. They could be used as inputs to an independent forward model spectral radiance calculation for comparison to TES L1B radiance spectra.

Atmospheric vertical profile estimates and associated errors (diagonals and covariance matrices), along with retrieved surface temperature, cloud effective optical depth, column estimates, quality flags, averaging kernels and a priori constraint vectors. Updated GMAO a priori values.
Profiles can be compared to other measurements or models of this species or used as input to global chemical/dynamical models
